<![CDATA[<h1>Set the Neovim</h1><p>Author: D-Sketon(xxx@example.com)</p>
        
          <p><del>Firstly</del> Begin by installing neovim.</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"><code class="language-zsh" data-lang="zsh"><span class="line"><span class="cl">sudo pacman -S neovim
</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Use the <code>.lua</code> to conigure <em>NeoVim</em></p>
<blockquote>
<p>can use the <code>.vim</code> to configure <em>NeoVim</em> too.</p>
</blockquote>
<h2 id="set-the-config-path-of-nvim">
<a class="header-anchor" href="#set-the-config-path-of-nvim"></a>
Set the config path of nvim
</h2><p>In the linux system, the <code>nvim</code> config directory local in the <code>~/.config/nvim</code>. This PATH also called <code>runtime path</code> , <em>NeoVim</em> read the <code>~/.config/nvim/init.lua</code> by default.</p>
<p>In theory, all the config things can be placed in this <code>.lua</code>, but not a good idea.</p>
        
